## 3. Step-by-Step: What We Did and Why

### Step 0 — Problem Framing ([problem_framing.md](file:///d:/2ndojt/sms-spam-classifier/docs/problem_framing.md))

Before writing any code, we defined **5 analytical questions**:

| # | Question | Why It Matters |
|---|----------|----------------|
| 1 | What is the baseline spam rate? | If 87% is ham, a "predict ham always" model gets 87% accuracy — so accuracy alone is misleading |
| 2 | Which spam patterns pose the highest risk? | Helps the content team prioritise enforcement |
| 3 | At what confidence level can we auto-block vs flag? | Not all predictions are equal — need a threshold strategy |
| 4 | Which legitimate messages get misclassified? | False positives erode user trust |
| 5 | How much manual review effort does the classifier save? | Quantifies the business value |

---

### Step 1 — Data Ingestion ([ingest.py](file:///d:/2ndojt/sms-spam-classifier/src/ingest.py))

**What it does** (5 sub-steps):

1. **Download** — downloads the dataset from a GitHub mirror of the UCI repository (no API key needed). Saves to [data/raw/spam.csv](file:///d:/2ndojt/sms-spam-classifier/data/raw/spam.csv).

2. **Load & fix encoding** — reads with `latin-1` encoding because the file has special characters (£, €, accented letters) that break UTF-8. Tries TSV format first, falls back to CSV.

3. **Clean columns** — drops unnamed/junk columns (Kaggle version has `Unnamed: 2, 3, 4`), standardises column names to `['label', 'message']`.

4. **Remove duplicates** — drops exact-duplicate messages (keeps first occurrence). **Why?** Duplicates cause data leakage if the same message appears in both train and test sets.

5. **Validate** — asserts: exactly 2 columns, labels are only `'ham'`/`'spam'`, no nulls remain, at least 4,000 rows survive.

**Output**: [data/cleaned/sms_clean.csv](file:///d:/2ndojt/sms-spam-classifier/data/cleaned/sms_clean.csv) — the single "clean" dataset every subsequent script reads.

> **Viva tip**: *"Why latin-1?"* → Every byte 0x00–0xFF maps to a valid character, so it never raises a decode error. UTF-8 is stricter and fails on certain special characters in this dataset.

