### Step 3 — Label Sanity Checks ([labels.py](file:///d:/2ndojt/sms-spam-classifier/src/labels.py))

**What it does**: 5 checks specifically on the target (label) column:

| Check | Purpose | Why? |
|-------|---------|------|
| **Allowed values** | Verify only `'ham'` and `'spam'` exist | A typo like `'Spam'` or `'Ham '` silently creates a 3rd class |
| **No nulls** | Zero NaN in labels | A null label = no ground truth → can't train on it |
| **Class balance** | Compute imbalance ratio | ~6:1 ratio means accuracy is misleading; need F1/precision/recall |
| **Spot check** | Print 5 random samples per class | Humans eyeball for semantic label errors (spam labelled as ham) |
| **Majority baseline** | Accuracy of "predict ham always" | ~87% — this is the floor; any model must beat this |

**Outputs**:
- [outputs/reports/label_sanity_report.json](file:///d:/2ndojt/sms-spam-classifier/outputs/reports/label_sanity_report.json)
- [outputs/figures/label_distribution_pie.png](file:///d:/2ndojt/sms-spam-classifier/outputs/figures/label_distribution_pie.png)

> **Viva tip**: *"Why is ~87% accuracy a bad metric?"* → Because a dummy model that always predicts "ham" already achieves 87%. We need **precision** (of messages flagged as spam, how many truly are?), **recall** (of all spam, how many did we catch?), and **F1** (harmonic mean of both).

